WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.080
So, imagine for a second that you are standing in the middle of this infinite, just completely featureless white room.

00:10.240 --> 00:12.600
Like a sensory deprivation tank that you can move.

00:12.720 --> 00:14.620
Yeah, exactly. Like a total void.

00:15.160 --> 00:18.160
And you have no tethers. There are no walls anywhere.

00:18.760 --> 00:24.780
You have the mechanical ability to walk in absolutely any direction you want.

00:24.780 --> 00:31.740
You could, I don't know, sprint in zigzags or leap in these chaotic, completely unpredictable spirals.

00:31.980 --> 00:37.600
You could even teleport your weight from one coordinate to another without crossing the space in between.

00:38.140 --> 00:42.420
Basically, you have infinite geometric possibilities at your disposal.

00:42.620 --> 00:43.460
You can do whatever you want.

00:43.600 --> 00:50.900
Right. But for some reason, every single time you need to move, you deliberately put one foot exactly in front of the other.

00:50.900 --> 00:57.700
You lock yourself into a perfectly straight, super predictable, and, well, highly restricted line.

00:57.900 --> 00:59.400
It's completely counterintuitive.

00:59.580 --> 01:10.380
Exactly. Why? I mean, why would a system that has the capacity to do literally anything choose to just operate inside this tiny, constrained little box?

01:10.640 --> 01:13.880
It is, um, it's a profound paradox, really.

01:13.880 --> 01:21.600
And if we take that infinite white room and we apply it to cognitive science, we aren't talking about walking anymore.

01:21.700 --> 01:22.840
We're talking about human thought.

01:23.040 --> 01:25.260
Right. So, welcome to the Deep Dive.

01:25.700 --> 01:27.820
Today, we are looking at your brain.

01:28.260 --> 01:33.380
We are unpacking a single, just incredibly dense piece of source material.

01:33.740 --> 01:40.380
It's a paper that was published in May of 2026 by an independent researcher named Flyxion.

01:40.380 --> 01:49.220
And the title is a mouthful. It's called Amplitwist Cascades, Biological Priors, and the Geometry of Cognitive Transformation.

01:49.480 --> 01:50.840
Yeah, quite a title.

01:51.180 --> 01:56.260
But our mission today is to decode this whole geometric account of human thought.

01:56.260 --> 02:05.040
We are going to explore why your brain, which, you know, theoretically has the computational power to think in these infinite chaotic directions,

02:05.360 --> 02:11.540
actually forces itself to run on these ancient, highly restricted evolutionary tracks.

02:11.840 --> 02:18.040
And we'll look at why an AI that, you know, perfectly matches your answers might actually just be an illusion of intelligence.

02:18.040 --> 02:20.020
Yeah, that part blew my mind.

02:20.320 --> 02:31.180
We'll also get into the mathematical proof from the paper that suggests that how you arrive at an answer is fundamentally more important than the answer itself.

02:32.320 --> 02:34.360
So, okay, let's unpack this.

02:34.480 --> 02:44.880
And I want to start with the very first major distinction that Flyxion introduces, which is this idea of capacity versus implementation.

02:44.880 --> 02:54.360
Right. So to really understand the mechanics of how we actually think, we first have to recognize that when we talk about computation.

02:54.760 --> 02:57.460
Especially right now with all the AI stuff happening.

02:57.480 --> 03:00.240
Exactly. Especially with the rise of artificial intelligence.

03:00.640 --> 03:03.580
We usually only focus on one half of the equation.

03:03.640 --> 03:03.980
Right.

03:04.420 --> 03:08.320
We tend to focus really heavily on what's called expressive capacity.

03:08.680 --> 03:10.060
Expressive capacity. Okay.

03:10.060 --> 03:20.000
Yeah. Expressive capacity is basically the full envelope of what a system could theoretically compute if it used every single resource it had available to it.

03:20.120 --> 03:21.240
So that's the whole white room.

03:21.520 --> 03:22.340
That's the white room.

03:23.020 --> 03:28.280
And artificial neural networks are deliberately designed to exploit this full capacity.

03:28.420 --> 03:35.500
I mean, they use every dimension, every parameter, just to approximate a mathematical function and brute force and output.

03:35.500 --> 03:41.840
So they're the ones in the white room doing the zigzags and the, like, multidimensional leaps across the space.

03:41.960 --> 03:42.320
Exactly.

03:42.700 --> 03:46.340
They aren't bound by any sort of internal rules about how to move.

03:46.540 --> 03:49.740
They just know they need to reach the destination.

03:50.100 --> 03:52.880
Precisely. They just roam the entire coordinate space.

03:53.860 --> 03:58.260
But biological systems, like our brains, they just do not do that.

03:58.260 --> 04:05.260
Biology stays inside what Flyxion calls a, well, a narrow, prior-shaped corridor.

04:05.500 --> 04:07.120
A prior-shaped corridor.

04:07.340 --> 04:07.520
Right.

04:07.660 --> 04:17.920
And in the paper, Flyxion really emphasizes that this massive gap between what our brains could theoretically do and what they actually do, it isn't a flaw.

04:18.060 --> 04:19.000
It's not a bub.

04:19.000 --> 04:26.260
No, it's not a biological limitation that we should try to somehow overcome or, like, hack our brains to get past.

04:26.860 --> 04:29.760
It literally is the shape of human cognition.

04:30.280 --> 04:33.240
Brains just don't randomly approximate functions.

04:33.380 --> 04:38.000
They select these safe, stable, heavily restricted trajectories.

04:38.760 --> 04:42.740
I'm trying to picture the evolutionary logic behind that.

04:42.820 --> 04:46.740
Like, it kind of reminds me of having a really finely tuned sports car.

04:46.860 --> 04:47.660
Okay, let's hear it.

04:47.660 --> 04:50.540
Let's say it's a Formula One racing machine.

04:50.980 --> 04:58.140
It's totally capable of going, I don't know, 200 miles per hour and taking these hairpin turns at massive G-forces.

04:58.400 --> 05:00.300
That's its theoretical capacity.

05:00.620 --> 05:00.840
Right.

05:01.100 --> 05:04.520
But you are permanently stuck driving it in a school zone.

05:05.020 --> 05:13.360
So the rules of the environment, the need for safety, or I guess what Flyxion calls the prior, they restrict the car to 15 miles per hour.

05:13.360 --> 05:19.160
So we are basically artificially speed limited by our own biology.

05:19.720 --> 05:23.500
The F1 car analogy is, well, it's a really good starting point.

05:23.500 --> 05:29.100
But let's tweak it to be just a bit more biologically accurate based on the paper.

05:29.260 --> 05:30.060
Okay, lay it on me.

05:30.320 --> 05:36.640
It's not just that the car is forced into a school zone by external arbitrary rules like the speed limit sign.

05:36.740 --> 05:37.060
Mm-hmm.

05:37.180 --> 05:46.020
It's that the engine itself will literally overheat and just shake the car to pieces if it tries to go 200 miles per hour on that specific conceptual terrain.

05:46.020 --> 05:48.360
Oh, wow. So the car destroys itself?

05:48.520 --> 05:48.660
Yeah.

05:49.200 --> 05:56.100
The paper notes that biological systems are strikingly low-dimensional relative to the spaces they nominally act upon.

05:56.900 --> 06:04.560
Our neural population dynamics, which is just the actual firing patterns of our neurons, they occupy a very small number of stable modes.

06:04.980 --> 06:08.520
Meaning we only have a few safe ways to run the engine.

06:08.760 --> 06:09.260
Exactly.

06:09.260 --> 06:18.400
So when you are thinking through a really complex problem, you aren't searching the entire database of all possible mathematical solutions.

06:18.800 --> 06:28.080
You are traveling down a very narrow corridor of thought because your brain knows it's the only pathway it can dynamically support.

06:28.420 --> 06:33.160
If it leaves the corridor, it loses metabolic and cognitive stability.

06:33.160 --> 06:44.100
Wait. So if I try to push the engine too hard, like if I really try to force my brain to operate outside this comfortable biological corridor, what actually happens?

06:44.120 --> 06:49.320
Because I don't just like shut down like a crashed computer, right? My brain doesn't just blue screen.

06:49.500 --> 06:54.040
No, you don't crash. And this is actually a really brilliant observation in the paper.

06:54.460 --> 06:58.040
This is where we see what Flyxion calls directional failures.

06:58.040 --> 06:59.680
Directional failures.

06:59.680 --> 07:11.060
Right. When you force a biological system into a task that requires an impossible, unsupported jump through cognitive space, we don't fail randomly.

07:11.380 --> 07:14.400
We don't just output pure static or gibberish.

07:14.580 --> 07:15.520
Okay, so what do we do?

07:15.940 --> 07:24.060
We fail by trying to pull that impossible task back into our comfortable biological corridor.

07:24.060 --> 07:29.260
We fail in the direction of the nearest familiar rule.

07:29.600 --> 07:31.820
Oh man, that makes a lot of sense.

07:32.100 --> 07:40.980
Like, okay, think about when someone tries to learn a really complex new concept, say quantum mechanics.

07:41.180 --> 07:42.020
Perfect example.

07:42.460 --> 07:49.140
And they just cannot grasp the math of wave-particle duality because it's completely unintuitive.

07:49.620 --> 07:52.500
They don't just output gibberish when you ask them about it.

07:52.500 --> 07:58.280
They fall back to visualizing, like, tiny billiard balls bouncing off each other.

07:58.360 --> 07:59.220
Yes, exactly.

07:59.420 --> 08:02.140
The billiard ball is the comfortable biological corridor.

08:02.440 --> 08:07.800
The brain substitutes a familiar stable concept for the impossible mathematical leap.

08:07.880 --> 08:08.880
That is exactly it.

08:08.960 --> 08:15.000
You impose a spurious, fake, intermediate step just to make the cognitive leap feel stable to you.

08:15.260 --> 08:19.100
You anchor it to something your physical neural architecture already knows how to process.

08:19.520 --> 08:22.200
Because my brain knows what a billiard ball looks like.

08:22.200 --> 08:27.480
A pure AI function, approximator on the other hand, wouldn't do that.

08:27.560 --> 08:36.860
It would just map the complex input directly to the complex output, entirely divorced from whether that mapping actually makes sense to a physical body.

08:37.440 --> 08:41.100
But your brain has to drag the whole concept through the school zone.

08:41.100 --> 08:42.920
That is so wild.

08:42.920 --> 08:52.680
Okay, so if human thought is restricted to this narrow, low-speed corridor, what is the actual vehicle driving down it?

08:52.740 --> 08:55.720
Like, what is the fundamental unit of movement here?

08:55.800 --> 09:00.580
Because, you know, we know neurons fire, but neurons firing isn't a thought.

09:01.060 --> 09:04.860
How do we geometrically move from concept A to concept B?

09:04.860 --> 09:08.740
That brings us to the real mathematical engine of Flyxion's paper.

09:09.220 --> 09:14.660
It's a concept that they actually borrowed from Tristan Needham's work on visual complex analysis.

09:15.160 --> 09:18.700
But Flyxion applies it here to cognitive representations.

09:19.120 --> 09:21.140
It's called the amplitwist operator.

09:21.320 --> 09:22.180
The amplitwist.

09:22.180 --> 09:24.820
I have to say, it sounds like a 1960s dance craze.

09:25.100 --> 09:26.340
Do the amplitwist.

09:26.480 --> 09:27.680
Yeah, it really does.

09:27.820 --> 09:28.020
Yeah.

09:28.020 --> 09:30.700
But its mathematical implications are profound.

09:31.540 --> 09:36.500
In standard complex analysis, you have these local similarity transformations.

09:37.700 --> 09:41.980
Flyxion defines the cognitive ampliwist as a mathematical triplet.

09:42.640 --> 09:44.740
It consists of three specific operations.

09:44.980 --> 09:45.220
Okay.

09:45.740 --> 09:47.340
Rho, theta, and pi.

09:47.640 --> 09:50.400
Okay, let me make sure I'm tracking the terminology from the paper.

09:50.940 --> 09:52.000
Rho is amplitude.

09:53.180 --> 09:55.200
Theta is a twist or rotation.

09:55.640 --> 09:57.240
And pi is projection.

09:57.580 --> 09:57.880
Correct.

09:58.020 --> 10:04.740
But what does that actually mean when I am, you know, having a thought, like, physically in my head?

10:04.840 --> 10:05.720
Oh, let's ground it.

10:06.560 --> 10:09.700
Rho, the amplitude, is the scaling factor.

10:10.320 --> 10:13.480
In a neural network, this translates to gain or precision.

10:14.120 --> 10:19.220
Think of it as how loudly a particular concept is being broadcast in your working memory.

10:19.360 --> 10:21.880
Like turning up the volume on a specific idea.

10:22.040 --> 10:22.520
Exactly.

10:22.940 --> 10:26.120
Then you have theta, which is the twist or the rotation.

10:26.120 --> 10:30.040
This represents a change in direction in your mental representation space.

10:30.040 --> 10:32.280
So shifting the relationship between concepts.

10:32.340 --> 10:36.720
And finally, pi is a nonlinear projection or a contraction.

10:36.720 --> 10:40.220
Now, why do we need the projection part?

10:40.220 --> 10:43.060
The scale and twist make sense, but why projection?

10:43.060 --> 10:45.680
Well, because the real world isn't linear.

10:45.680 --> 10:55.320
If our brains only used linear transformations, just scaling and rotating, we could never learn complex, nuanced relationships.

10:55.320 --> 11:04.400
The projection introduces the nonlinearity that's absolutely required to squish or stretch the conceptual space.

11:04.400 --> 11:08.820
It's what allows us to categorize things and draw hard boundaries.

11:08.980 --> 11:10.160
Oh, okay.

11:10.300 --> 11:22.340
And when your brain applies these three operators sequentially, so it's scaling, rotating, and projecting over and over again, they form what Flyxion calls amplitwist cascades.

11:22.340 --> 11:35.240
You know, here's where it gets really interesting to me, because when I was reading this specific breakdown of the amplitwist in the paper, I immediately thought about editing a photo on a smartphone.

11:35.460 --> 11:36.140
Oh, that's interesting.

11:36.260 --> 11:40.340
The photo analogy works quite well for the visual surface of this concept.

11:40.620 --> 11:42.000
Walk me through how you're picturing it.

11:42.200 --> 11:46.780
Well, think about what you do when you open an image in an editor to fix it, right?

11:46.780 --> 11:52.940
First, you might pinch the screen to zoom in on a specific detail, like, I don't know, someone's face.

11:53.240 --> 11:54.540
That's scaling it up.

11:54.600 --> 11:56.840
That's your amplitude, your row.

11:57.160 --> 12:01.820
You are increasing the precision of that specific data point so you can focus on it.

12:02.400 --> 12:10.300
Then, you realize the horizon in the background is a little crooked, so you use two fingers to rotate the image.

12:10.360 --> 12:10.840
It's a twist.

12:11.000 --> 12:11.280
Exactly.

12:11.400 --> 12:12.520
That's the twist, the theta.

12:12.620 --> 12:15.120
You've changed the directional orientation of the whole thing.

12:15.120 --> 12:26.200
And then, finally, you apply, like, a high-contrast color filter to change the fundamental mood of the picture squashing the brights and crushing the darks.

12:26.900 --> 12:30.260
That's your non-linear projection, the pie.

12:30.420 --> 12:32.100
That's a great way to visualize it.

12:32.520 --> 12:39.520
Flyxion is arguing that our brains do this exact three-step photo editing process, but with abstract concepts, right?

12:39.520 --> 12:49.340
Yes, but underneath that visual surface of the analogy, we have to remember we are ultimately talking about vector spaces and actual neural firing patterns.

12:49.580 --> 12:51.540
So, your analogy is structurally perfect.

12:51.940 --> 12:52.120
Yeah.

12:52.180 --> 12:56.160
We zoom in on an idea which is increasing neural gain.

12:56.160 --> 13:03.580
We rotate its meaning in our mental space, which is shifting lateral inhibition to change the conceptual vector.

13:03.840 --> 13:10.280
And we filter it through our existing biases and knowledge, which is that non-linear projection.

13:10.500 --> 13:10.620
Yeah.

13:10.620 --> 13:16.620
And the crazy part is we do this thousands of times a second in these massive cascades.

13:16.620 --> 13:31.200
What's totally staggering to me is that if these cascades are the universal language of transformation, then literally any thought, no matter how complex or deep, is just a sequence of pinches, rotations, and filters.

13:31.200 --> 13:31.760
Yeah.

13:31.980 --> 13:42.020
And what's fascinating here is that in the paper, Flyxion makes a point that these aren't just abstract functions hiding in some black box, which is usually how we treat deep learning models.

13:42.040 --> 13:42.280
Right.

13:42.460 --> 13:43.680
The AI black box.

13:43.700 --> 13:44.260
Exactly.

13:44.880 --> 13:48.720
In this theory, they're geometrically interpretable local operators.

13:49.040 --> 13:52.640
Flyxion is proposing that we can actually see the geometry of a thought.

13:52.640 --> 14:01.640
The mathematical proof in the paper shows that, with enough depth, an amplitwist cascade can theoretically compute anything.

14:02.640 --> 14:09.660
It has the exact same expressive power as the universal approximation theorems that are used to build large language models.

14:09.660 --> 14:25.000
Which means, if we had the right measurement tools, like some incredibly advanced brain scanner, we could theoretically map the exact sequence of twists and scales a person uses to arrive at a complex belief.

14:25.100 --> 14:26.640
We could map the whole past.

14:26.720 --> 14:38.740
We could mathematically chart how someone, like, zooms, rotates, and filters their way into a specific political stance, or a really complex moral philosophy.

14:38.740 --> 14:40.460
In principle, yes.

14:41.300 --> 14:52.700
If a belief is just a final mental state that you arrived at through a sequence of cognitive transformations, then it is literally just the endpoint of an amplitwist cascade.

14:53.360 --> 15:03.040
You started at some baseline, and your brain applied a specific, highly structured sequence of amplitudes, twists, and projections to land on that exact belief.

15:03.040 --> 15:10.720
But wait, if the amplitwist is the vehicle-like, if it's the photo editor making the changes, what is guiding the editing process?

15:11.020 --> 15:11.380
What do you mean?

15:11.740 --> 15:14.700
I mean, why do I twist an idea left instead of right?

15:14.840 --> 15:18.220
Why do I zoom in on one specific detail and completely ignore another?

15:18.560 --> 15:22.200
There has to be some sort of environment or map shaping these decisions, right?

15:22.600 --> 15:23.160
There is.

15:23.160 --> 15:29.240
If the amplitwist is the vehicle, we now have to look at the terrain it's driving over.

15:30.140 --> 15:36.020
Flyxion models this conceptual terrain using something called the RSVP fields.

15:36.460 --> 15:37.620
RSVP fields.

15:38.020 --> 15:39.420
Like a party invitation.

15:39.760 --> 15:44.720
Right, but in this case, it stands for Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum.

15:44.900 --> 15:45.360
Got it.

15:45.360 --> 15:52.580
It defines the entirety of your cognitive state space using three very distinct mathematical fields.

15:52.580 --> 15:56.220
Okay, let's break down the RSVP fields for the listener.

15:56.540 --> 15:57.720
What are the three components?

15:58.340 --> 16:01.740
First is the scalar field, which is represented by the Greek letter phi.

16:02.320 --> 16:04.040
This is semantic salience.

16:04.600 --> 16:06.520
But simply put, it is the goal.

16:06.960 --> 16:09.760
It is the destination that your thought is trying to reach.

16:09.820 --> 16:10.520
Okay, the goal.

16:10.640 --> 16:13.260
Second is the vector field, or lowercase v.

16:13.740 --> 16:15.920
This represents conceptual velocity.

16:15.920 --> 16:23.660
It measures how fast and in what specific conceptual direction your current thought is changing at any given moment.

16:23.780 --> 16:24.600
Speed and direction.

16:25.180 --> 16:25.380
Right.

16:25.620 --> 16:28.280
And third is the entropy field, or uppercase S.

16:28.660 --> 16:35.240
This represents cognitive uncertainty or, like, structural disorder or whatever task you're trying to do.

16:35.240 --> 16:43.160
Okay, so if I try to guess how these interact, salience is the goal pulling me forward.

16:43.800 --> 16:52.480
So there must be some sort of metric for how well my current speed, my velocity, is matching up with that goal, right?

16:52.540 --> 16:57.580
Like a cognitive compass or a speedometer to tell me if I'm actually getting any closer.

16:57.580 --> 16:58.160
Exactly.

16:58.820 --> 17:05.680
And the metric that emerges from the interaction of those specific fields is what Flicection calls phase alignment.

17:06.560 --> 17:15.120
Phase alignment is simply the angle between your mental velocity, where you are currently going, and the salience gradient, where you actually need to be.

17:15.300 --> 17:21.920
Okay, to make sure this is perfectly clear, let's try to ground this RSVP terrain in something physical.

17:21.920 --> 17:29.440
Because when you say gradients and velocity and entropy, it just sounds like a physics problem about a landscape.

17:29.660 --> 17:30.940
Is it a literal landscape?

17:31.400 --> 17:35.340
Well, a geographical metaphor is actually the most accurate way to visualize it.

17:35.460 --> 17:35.560
Yeah.

17:35.720 --> 17:38.140
Imagine a river flowing down the side of a mountain.

17:38.460 --> 17:39.500
Okay, a mountain river.

17:39.500 --> 17:45.200
The steep slope of the mountain, the actual gravity actively pulling the water downward toward the ocean.

17:45.720 --> 17:47.060
That is the salience field.

17:47.580 --> 17:50.460
It is the goal state, pulling your thoughts toward a resolution.

17:50.720 --> 17:51.340
I'm with you.

17:51.340 --> 18:01.120
The actual water current, the speed in the exact direction the water molecules are moving at any given millisecond, is your velocity field.

18:01.120 --> 18:09.300
So if the water is rushing straight down the steepest, clearest part of the mountain, my thought is perfectly aligned with my goal.

18:09.660 --> 18:09.980
Yes.

18:10.540 --> 18:16.260
Perfect phase alignment means the angle between your velocity and the mountain slope is zero.

18:17.200 --> 18:19.340
You're heading straight toward the solution.

18:19.340 --> 18:24.000
The cognitive processing feels totally effortless.

18:24.540 --> 18:25.980
It's almost like a flow state.

18:26.240 --> 18:28.360
That feeling when everything just clicks.

18:28.560 --> 18:29.120
Exactly.

18:29.120 --> 18:36.820
But what happens if the river hits a massive field of boulders, or like a really flat, confusing plateau?

18:38.020 --> 18:40.320
That is where the entropy field comes in.

18:40.840 --> 18:45.120
The rocks and structural obstacles represent cognitive uncertainty.

18:45.900 --> 18:49.280
When the water hits a rock, it can't just go straight down anymore.

18:49.360 --> 18:50.800
It has to swirl around it.

18:50.800 --> 18:53.100
It spins, it creates little whirlpools.

18:53.200 --> 18:53.640
Exactly.

18:53.900 --> 18:57.000
And that spinning creates what the paper defines as vorticity.

18:57.080 --> 18:57.640
Vorticity.

18:58.160 --> 19:00.460
Vorticity is cognitive turbulence.

19:01.420 --> 19:02.540
It's mental inefficiency.

19:02.540 --> 19:14.240
If your phase alignment is bad, say the angle between your thought vector and the goal is closer to 90 degrees, you aren't actually moving toward the goal anymore.

19:14.440 --> 19:17.740
You are moving sideways, or you're just spinning your wheels.

19:17.740 --> 19:27.320
A highly uncertain, high-entropy task suppresses smooth thought and generates massive vorticity.

19:27.740 --> 19:29.340
Man, vorticity.

19:29.520 --> 19:31.280
That is such a visceral word.

19:31.660 --> 19:36.680
I feel like we all know exactly what mental vorticity feels like in our daily lives.

19:36.780 --> 19:37.560
Oh, absolutely.

19:37.900 --> 19:40.580
I'll give you a real-world example from my own life.

19:40.640 --> 19:46.600
A few weeks ago, I sat down to play this incredibly complex, heavy strategy board game with some friends.

19:46.600 --> 19:48.700
Oh, those rulebooks can be brutal.

19:48.960 --> 19:49.060
Right.

19:49.280 --> 19:54.720
I'm reading the rulebook, and the rules are just so dense, they rely on mechanics I've literally never seen before.

19:55.180 --> 20:05.800
I am reading the words on the page, my eyes are scanning the paragraphs, I am burning calories, trying to understand it, but I am not actually moving closer to comprehension.

20:06.000 --> 20:06.460
You're stuck.

20:06.700 --> 20:08.820
I am caught in a mental eddy.

20:08.820 --> 20:17.400
My brain is swirling around the concepts, but completely failing to align with the actual goal of understanding how to play the game.

20:17.880 --> 20:24.080
That friction, that mental exhaustion without any actual progress, that's vorticity, right?

20:24.480 --> 20:27.840
That is a perfect encapsulation of poor phase alignment.

20:28.560 --> 20:34.340
The trajectory of your thought is no longer pointing in the direction of the task gradient.

20:34.560 --> 20:35.600
Because of the rocks.

20:35.600 --> 20:36.000
Right.

20:36.300 --> 20:42.660
The rocks, in your board game example, are the unfamiliar mechanics, the high entropy of the new rules.

20:43.320 --> 20:52.020
You are generating rotational structure in your neural representation space, but you're making absolutely zero forward progress.

20:52.520 --> 20:55.400
Which brings us to a massive question that the paper gets into.

20:55.400 --> 21:08.200
If an AI was reading that exact same board game rule book, it wouldn't experience vorticity, it wouldn't get confused and spin its reels, it would just ingest the text and map the inputs to the outputs perfectly.

21:08.360 --> 21:09.060
In seconds.

21:09.280 --> 21:09.520
Right.

21:09.760 --> 21:14.000
So why do humans have those rocks in our mental river at all?

21:14.000 --> 21:24.240
Like, if the brain is this incredible, hyper-advanced supercomputer, why doesn't it just bulldoze through the entropy in a straight line the way a language model does?

21:24.600 --> 21:31.160
Well, because to bulldoze through high entropy requires an immense amount of unconstrained computational capacity.

21:31.160 --> 21:39.080
And as we established earlier with the F1 car in the school zone, human biology operates under incredibly strict constraints.

21:39.920 --> 21:44.000
We have vorticity because we have an ancient evolutionary handbrake.

21:44.320 --> 21:46.580
Flinchin calls it the biological prior.

21:46.820 --> 21:47.920
The biological prior.

21:48.060 --> 21:48.280
Right.

21:48.280 --> 21:57.120
And to truly grasp what this prior actually is and why it exists, we have to look at biological structures called CPGs.

21:57.520 --> 21:58.960
Central pattern generators.

21:58.960 --> 22:04.820
This was the moment in the paper where the biology and the dense math suddenly fused together for me.

22:05.340 --> 22:06.740
Tell us about CPGs.

22:07.200 --> 22:11.100
Central pattern generators are these ancient, highly conserved neural circuits.

22:11.100 --> 22:13.600
They're found across almost the entire animal kingdom.

22:13.600 --> 22:27.360
Basically, they are localized networks of neurons that are responsible for producing rhythmic, coordinated motor outputs without needing continuous input from the brain or from sensory organs.

22:27.560 --> 22:31.040
So they are essentially autopilot rhythms for our bodies.

22:31.040 --> 22:41.300
Like, a dog automatically paddling its legs in the air, when you just hold it over a swimming pool, it doesn't have to formally learn how to swim or think about it.

22:41.460 --> 22:43.440
The rhythm just completely takes over.

22:43.700 --> 22:44.180
Precisely.

22:44.840 --> 22:46.820
Breathing is driven by a CPG.

22:47.080 --> 22:48.500
Chewing your food is a CPG.

22:49.060 --> 22:53.580
The undulating, side-to-side, swimming motion of a fish, that's a CPG.

22:54.480 --> 23:02.700
Once the brain sends a single go signal, the central pattern generator just handles the entire complex rhythm.

23:02.820 --> 23:04.340
You don't have to micromanage it.

23:04.340 --> 23:06.540
No, you don't have to consciously calculate.

23:06.660 --> 23:11.800
Okay, contract the diaphragm, lower the air pressure in the lungs, hold it, release the diaphragm.

23:11.800 --> 23:15.680
The CPG runs that stable, low-energy loop for you.

23:15.680 --> 23:35.300
What Flisham posits, and this is arguably the most radical biological claim in the entire paper, is that our highest levels of cognitive computation, our deep, abstract reasoning, actually operate via a biological prior that is modeled on these exact same CPG-like dynamics.

23:35.300 --> 23:36.620
Wait, wait, wait, wait.

23:36.620 --> 23:53.360
So my brain forces abstract, complex thoughts, like doing algebra or writing a script, to run on the exact same kind of rhythmic, low-dimensional autopilot tracks that it uses to make my lungs breathe or my jaw chew.

23:53.360 --> 24:00.180
Yes, the brain actively penalizes high-entropy paths because they are metabolically expensive.

24:00.580 --> 24:03.040
They drain your energy, and they're unstable.

24:03.480 --> 24:13.940
So when your brain needs to solve an abstract problem, it does not search a massive multidimensional database to find the mathematically optimal straight-line solution.

24:14.140 --> 24:14.940
Like an AI would.

24:14.980 --> 24:15.920
Like an AI would.

24:15.920 --> 24:20.600
Instead, it searches for a safe, CPG-supportable trajectory.

24:21.200 --> 24:25.960
It deliberately selects a cognitive path that can be broken down into stable, rhythmic steps.

24:26.120 --> 24:29.640
You know, I think of this like walking down a really busy city sidewalk.

24:29.800 --> 24:34.500
When I walk, I am not consciously calculating the physics of my movement.

24:34.500 --> 24:45.060
I'm not doing math on the friction coefficient of the concrete or like adjusting the exact vector of gravity for every single footstep.

24:45.240 --> 24:49.480
I just lean forward and let my walking rhythm generator take over.

24:50.440 --> 24:53.880
Walking is essentially just controlled falling caught by a rhythm.

24:54.420 --> 24:58.820
And Flyxion is arguing we do the exact same thing for abstract reasoning and language.

24:58.960 --> 25:01.300
We just string together mental footsteps.

25:01.300 --> 25:01.660
Yeah.

25:02.040 --> 25:08.160
And if we connect this to the bigger picture, this beautifully explains why humans learn compositionally.

25:09.440 --> 25:12.380
Think about how a child learns mathematics.

25:12.720 --> 25:13.020
Okay.

25:13.620 --> 25:18.320
You do not, and you literally cannot, teach them calculus on day one.

25:18.780 --> 25:20.820
You teach them to count integers, one, two, three.

25:21.540 --> 25:25.800
Once the rhythm of counting is locked in and stable, you teach them addition.

25:26.160 --> 25:28.300
Which is just a new rhythm built on the old one.

25:28.720 --> 25:29.180
Exactly.

25:29.180 --> 25:35.500
You have to physically stabilize layer one in their neural architecture before you can even introduce layer two.

25:36.100 --> 25:36.320
Why?

25:37.180 --> 25:43.760
Because our internal cognitive rhythm generators can only handle one level of the hierarchy at a time.

25:44.320 --> 25:52.120
The paper specifically states that entropy weighting continuously pulls our mental trajectory toward the highest prior path.

25:52.640 --> 25:56.500
We are biologically constrained to build our thoughts rhythmically.

25:56.500 --> 26:02.180
I want to just pause and speculate on this for a second because the implications here are profound.

26:03.120 --> 26:25.880
Does this imply that our highest, most abstract philosophical thoughts like debating the ethics of artificial intelligence or contemplating the infinite expanse of the universe are fundamentally just evolutionary re-skins of the neural circuits our ancestors used to coordinate chewing their food or swimming away from a predator?

26:25.880 --> 26:30.040
That is exactly the implication of a CPG-based biological prior.

26:30.200 --> 26:30.420
Wow.

26:30.480 --> 26:40.500
We evolved these incredibly stable, perturbation-resistant dynamical circuits to move our physical bodies through physical space without falling over.

26:40.500 --> 26:49.840
As the human cortex expanded over millions of years, we didn't invent entirely new mathematical ways to process information.

26:50.280 --> 27:00.180
We just repurposed that exact same rhythmic geometric machinery to move our abstract representations through conceptual space.

27:00.180 --> 27:10.480
So the F1 car is restricted to the school zone because the school zone is the only terrain where our ancient rhythmic engines actually know how to operate without breaking down.

27:10.700 --> 27:10.960
Yes.

27:11.600 --> 27:21.640
You are literally navigating the abstract concept of justice using the exact same geometric rules your physical body uses to walk upstairs.

27:21.880 --> 27:23.440
That is deeply humbling.

27:23.660 --> 27:26.740
My most profound existential thoughts are just mental chewing.

27:26.960 --> 27:27.440
Basically.

27:27.440 --> 27:28.860
But it makes perfect sense.

27:29.220 --> 27:41.440
However, if our thoughts are just trajectories moving along these rhythmic tracks, like if thinking is literally an action, a movement, then Flyxion argues we need to fundamentally redefine what it means to actually know something.

27:41.720 --> 27:41.940
Right?

27:41.980 --> 27:43.580
We have to redefine meaning itself.

27:44.000 --> 27:44.400
We do.

27:45.000 --> 27:50.080
And this leads to what might be the most philosophically aggressive part of the paper.

27:50.840 --> 27:54.640
Section 5 essentially shatters the illusion of static meaning.

27:54.640 --> 27:55.200
Right.

27:55.660 --> 28:00.020
The paper aggressively pushes back against something called static encoding.

28:00.820 --> 28:07.140
It claims that meaning is not a specific point or like a specific pattern of neurons letting up in your brain.

28:07.260 --> 28:09.640
Meaning is trajectory equivalence.

28:10.460 --> 28:10.740
Right.

28:10.740 --> 28:26.620
To put this in context, the standard simplified view in neuroscience and even in cognitive psychology often treats a concept like, let's take the concept of an apple as a specific pattern of neural activation, a static state.

28:27.020 --> 28:31.640
You activate the apple network of neurons and boom, you have the meaning of an apple.

28:31.920 --> 28:35.740
It's treated like a physical object just sitting in a box inside your head.

28:35.840 --> 28:38.420
Like a dictionary definition stored on a shelf.

28:38.420 --> 28:38.980
Exactly.

28:39.660 --> 28:39.780
Yeah.

28:40.340 --> 28:43.120
But Flyxion says this is completely backwards.

28:43.960 --> 28:45.420
Meaning is not a state.

28:46.200 --> 28:50.240
Meaning is how a state behaves under a sequence of perturbations.

28:50.540 --> 28:52.680
How does behavior equal meaning?

28:53.420 --> 28:59.260
Let me try an analogy here to see if I'm grasping this idea of trajectory equivalence.

28:59.780 --> 29:02.840
Think about a digital file sitting on your computer desktop.

29:02.940 --> 29:03.840
Okay, I'm with you.

29:03.840 --> 29:07.280
Say you have an icon that looks like a PDF document.

29:08.280 --> 29:16.720
If you just look at the statting state, the icon just sitting there on the screen, you don't actually know what it means or even what it is.

29:16.760 --> 29:18.240
It could be a fake shortcut.

29:18.600 --> 29:20.960
It could be a completely corrupted file.

29:21.220 --> 29:25.640
You only actually know what that file means by perturbing it.

29:25.880 --> 29:26.940
By interacting with it.

29:26.940 --> 29:27.260
Right.

29:27.620 --> 29:29.160
You double click it to open it.

29:29.640 --> 29:31.100
You highlight the text.

29:31.220 --> 29:32.100
You edit a paragraph.

29:32.440 --> 29:34.120
You attach it to an email and send it.

29:34.680 --> 29:40.580
The true meaning of the file is revealed entirely by what it does when you interact with it.

29:40.860 --> 29:44.040
Not by what it statically is just sitting on the desktop.

29:44.720 --> 29:45.980
Is that what Flyxion means?

29:45.980 --> 29:50.940
That analogy captures the essence perfectly, but let's push it a little further into the math.

29:51.560 --> 29:53.500
What if I have a Mac and you have a PC?

29:54.020 --> 29:55.600
Okay, different operating systems.

29:55.860 --> 30:05.040
The underlying code, the actual static binary state of that file on my hard drive, is physically different from how it is stored on yours.

30:05.040 --> 30:16.080
Yet, if we both open the file, apply the same edits, and it produces the exact same result, the file holds the same meaning for both of us.

30:17.000 --> 30:24.040
Two mental states represent the exact same proposition only if they respond identically to the same sequence of transformations.

30:24.880 --> 30:25.180
Wow.

30:25.600 --> 30:28.480
Meaning is constituted by transformation and variance.

30:28.480 --> 30:40.780
If I take your mental file and I apply an amplitwist cascade to it, I scale it, I rotate it, I filter it, does it end up in the same place as my mental file when I apply the exact same cascade?

30:41.380 --> 30:43.720
If yes, then we share the meaning.

30:44.140 --> 30:49.440
Even if the actual physical static layout of our neurons started out looking completely different.

30:49.960 --> 30:50.440
Precisely.

30:50.580 --> 30:56.440
And this elegantly solves one of the oldest, most frustrating problems in cognitive science and philosophy.

30:56.440 --> 31:00.200
No two human brains are wired exactly the same way.

31:00.720 --> 31:03.840
The physical layout of your synapses is completely unique to you.

31:04.420 --> 31:08.100
So how can you and I both hold the exact same concept of democracy?

31:08.540 --> 31:17.000
Because if meaning requires static encoding, it's almost impossible for us to share a meaning because our static biological states are different.

31:17.340 --> 31:17.840
Exactly.

31:18.620 --> 31:24.620
But if meaning is trajectory equivalence, it doesn't matter that our static neural states are different.

31:24.620 --> 31:28.740
It only matters that our transformation geometries align.

31:29.720 --> 31:35.760
When subjected to the same logical questions, our thoughts travel down the same geometric paths.

31:36.220 --> 31:43.000
The paper explicitly ties this back to philosophy, specifically mentioning a philosopher named Brandom.

31:43.260 --> 31:43.560
Yes.

31:43.800 --> 31:46.920
Robert Brandom's inferential role, semantics.

31:46.920 --> 31:54.260
Back in the late 20th century, Brandom argued that the meaning of a concept isn't a picture in your head.

31:54.940 --> 31:58.740
Its meaning is defined entirely by its role in making inferences.

31:59.160 --> 32:00.200
What does that mean practically?

32:00.760 --> 32:06.100
It means asking, what does believing in democracy commit you to believing next?

32:06.880 --> 32:08.780
And what does it entitle you to argue?

32:09.500 --> 32:13.260
Meaning is what you can do with a concept in a logical argument.

32:13.260 --> 32:19.160
Flyxion acknowledges Brandom's brilliance here, but points out a historical flaw.

32:20.420 --> 32:23.600
Inferential role semantics has always been incredibly vague.

32:24.220 --> 32:28.320
It's really hard to quantify commitments and entitlements in a laboratory.

32:29.280 --> 32:34.060
Flyxion's paper provides a literal, geometric way to measure Brandom's theory.

32:34.060 --> 32:44.420
Okay, this is a beautiful philosophical framework, but I have to play the skeptic here for a minute.

32:44.940 --> 32:47.020
Flyxion insists this isn't just a theory.

32:47.200 --> 32:49.820
They claim this is actual falsifiable science.

32:50.380 --> 32:54.640
But how exactly do you test the geometry of a thought in a laboratory?

32:55.020 --> 33:00.360
I mean, you can't exactly stick a protractor into a participant's ear and measure the angle of their meaning.

33:00.360 --> 33:05.140
No, you definitely can't measure the angle directly with a physical tool.

33:05.940 --> 33:14.220
But you can design an experiment that measures behavioral responses and reaction time in a highly controlled conceptual environment.

33:14.960 --> 33:18.660
And this is exactly what Flyxion proposes in Section 9 of the paper.

33:19.260 --> 33:23.400
The proposed experiment uses what linguists call knots' words.

33:23.700 --> 33:25.680
Knots' words. Made-up words.

33:25.760 --> 33:26.440
Made-up words.

33:26.460 --> 33:27.620
Like the word blick.

33:28.260 --> 33:28.840
Exactly.

33:28.840 --> 33:36.660
The experiment forces participants to transform these made-up words across three very specific cognitive layers.

33:37.300 --> 33:42.500
First is the phonological layer, so maybe changing the stem blick to a verb form, like blicken.

33:42.820 --> 33:43.140
Okay.

33:43.540 --> 33:49.700
Second is the morphological layer, changing the grammatical role, like turning the verb into an agent, a blicker.

33:50.040 --> 33:58.460
And third is the semantic-pragmatic layer, applying a real-world context, like defining a blicker as a tool for blicking.

33:58.460 --> 34:04.320
Hold on, I'm reading this experiment design, and it feels like there is a massive methodological flaw.

34:04.840 --> 34:11.940
Yeah, if Flyxion is trying to map the geometry of actual human thought, why use gibberish words like blick?

34:12.600 --> 34:17.520
Doesn't that entirely defeat the purpose of testing real language and real meaning?

34:17.780 --> 34:20.360
Like, why not test people on real vocabulary?

34:20.700 --> 34:24.180
Like, transforming the word run into runner.

34:24.180 --> 34:28.440
It's actually a critical methodological choice, not a flaw.

34:29.220 --> 34:32.080
Real words carry heavy memorized baggage.

34:32.720 --> 34:39.200
If I asked you to transform run into runner, you aren't actually doing any geometric cognitive computation.

34:39.320 --> 34:40.400
Because I already know it.

34:40.400 --> 34:40.940
Exactly.

34:41.080 --> 34:43.080
You weren't using an amplitwist cascade.

34:43.460 --> 34:47.680
You were simply retrieving the memorized pair from your mental lexicon.

34:48.200 --> 34:50.460
You bypassed the geometric work entirely.

34:50.940 --> 34:58.640
To measure the pure geometry of the transformation, you have to force the brain into an environment where it cannot rely on rote memory.

34:58.640 --> 35:08.620
By using a controlled, artificial manifold of made-up words, the researchers can calculate the exact mathematical ground truth direction the thought should move in.

35:08.700 --> 35:09.480
Ah, I see.

35:09.640 --> 35:18.220
Because the researchers literally invented the word and the rules for how it changes, they know exactly what the perfect phase alignment angle should be.

35:18.480 --> 35:20.920
They built the mountain, so they know where the mountain slopes.

35:20.920 --> 35:21.600
Exactly.

35:22.260 --> 35:35.260
And the prediction of the experiment is that if the task is smoothly compositional, meaning, if the participant can take it step by step through the layers, rhythmically human subjects will show improving phase alignment.

35:35.800 --> 35:40.680
Over multiple trials, their mental trajectory will play more and more perfectly toward the target.

35:41.100 --> 35:46.720
And their mental vorticity, that turbulence and confusion, will decrease and stabilize.

35:47.180 --> 35:47.980
They learn the rhythm.

35:47.980 --> 35:51.600
They find the CPG track, they get in the groove of the rulebook.

35:51.800 --> 35:52.020
Right.

35:52.320 --> 35:54.360
But experiments always need a control group.

35:54.920 --> 35:57.840
What happens if you deliberately throw a wrench into the rhythm?

35:58.400 --> 36:01.320
The paper mentions non-compositional tasks.

36:01.620 --> 36:05.260
This is where we test the absolute limits of the biological prior.

36:06.080 --> 36:12.420
What happens if you give a participant a task that requires an illogical, non-compositional jump?

36:12.420 --> 36:19.020
A linguistic transformation that literally cannot be broken down into smooth, rhythmic steps.

36:19.520 --> 36:23.500
A point in the semantic space with no stable intermediate stage.

36:23.640 --> 36:26.240
So forcing the F1 car completely off the road.

36:26.620 --> 36:26.960
Yes.

36:27.900 --> 36:29.040
The prediction is stark.

36:29.420 --> 36:30.560
Humans will fail.

36:31.300 --> 36:34.480
But how they fail is the crucial data point.

36:34.480 --> 36:43.920
They will either show massive vorticity, huge spikes in mental turbulence and reaction time right at the boundary of the jump.

36:44.300 --> 36:57.140
Or, because of that biological prior pulling them desperately toward safety, they will invent a fake intermediate step to make the jump feel rhythmic, even though that step is logically wrong.

36:57.140 --> 37:01.880
They will hallucinate a bridge where there isn't one, just so they can keep walking rhythmically.

37:02.040 --> 37:06.240
That goes right back to the directional failure we talked about with quantum mechanics earlier.

37:06.560 --> 37:10.180
We invent the billiard balls to make the math feel safe.

37:10.560 --> 37:11.160
Exactly.

37:11.620 --> 37:14.400
Now, this is the pivot point of the entire paper.

37:15.060 --> 37:20.600
Compare that deeply human rhythmic failure to an artificial intelligence model.

37:20.600 --> 37:27.680
If you have the exact same non-compositional illogical task to a large language model, what does it do?

37:27.780 --> 37:30.560
It just memorizes the end point without breaking a sweat.

37:30.680 --> 37:31.640
It doesn't need a bridge.

37:31.720 --> 37:32.440
It doesn't need a rhythm.

37:32.620 --> 37:35.160
It just teleports from the input to the output.

37:35.600 --> 37:36.080
Precisely.

37:36.860 --> 37:39.280
The AI does not have a biological prior.

37:40.160 --> 37:49.620
It doesn't have a metabolism or a physical body that will collapse under high entropy.

37:49.620 --> 37:52.620
It just maps the input directly to the output.

37:53.260 --> 38:05.560
And that stark difference between how humans fail and how AI succeeds brings us to the ultimate metric of the paper and what is arguably the most important concept for the future of technology.

38:06.040 --> 38:06.280
Okay.

38:06.360 --> 38:15.900
We are diving into Section 7, the illusion of AI alignment and the introduction of a mathematical formula called geometric alignment loss.

38:16.180 --> 38:17.760
This raises an important question.

38:17.760 --> 38:21.060
Perhaps the most important question in current AI research.

38:21.700 --> 38:25.500
Are we currently measuring AI alignment completely wrong?

38:25.980 --> 38:27.920
Think about the industry standard right now.

38:28.440 --> 38:31.680
How do we know if an AI is aligned with human thinking?

38:32.160 --> 38:34.060
We ask it a complex question.

38:34.400 --> 38:40.040
And if it gives the right answer, an answer a human expert would give, we say it is aligned.

38:40.160 --> 38:41.840
We grade it purely on its output.

38:42.220 --> 38:42.380
Right.

38:42.380 --> 38:43.960
We just look at the destination.

38:44.200 --> 38:45.400
Did it solve the bar exam?

38:45.540 --> 38:46.860
Did it write a coherent essay?

38:47.020 --> 38:48.160
If yes, it's aligned.

38:48.660 --> 38:52.780
Flyxion's paper drops a total bombshell on this entire paradigm.

38:53.340 --> 38:57.760
The paper introduces geometric alignment loss, or L sub A.

38:57.760 --> 39:05.300
This formula mathematically compares the intermediate operator geometry between humans and language models.

39:05.540 --> 39:17.460
And the finding is that a language model can produce the exact same final answer as a human, but it traverses a completely disordered, entropy-insensitive path to get there.

39:17.460 --> 39:25.760
So they match endpoints perfectly, but the actual geometric journey, the sequence of amplitwists, is entirely different.

39:25.860 --> 39:26.300
Exactly.

39:26.860 --> 39:34.700
Flyxion argues that cognitive alignment is only real if the AI takes the same geometric path to get to the answer that a human would.

39:35.260 --> 39:37.160
Output agreement is just a mirage.

39:37.460 --> 39:40.380
This maps so perfectly to an experience we all had in school.

39:40.460 --> 39:43.220
It's like a student taking a complex calculus test.

39:43.380 --> 39:44.040
Yeah, let's hear it.

39:44.040 --> 39:52.060
The student, which represents the AI in this scenario, writes down the absolute correct final answer at the bottom of the page.

39:52.560 --> 39:53.820
The teacher is thrilled.

39:54.520 --> 39:59.320
But then, the teacher asks to look at the student's scratchpad to see their work.

39:59.860 --> 40:03.520
And when they look at the scratchpad, the work shown is complete gibberish.

40:03.520 --> 40:09.900
It uses alien logic, impossible mathematical leaps, teleportation across numbers.

40:09.900 --> 40:16.380
The student got the output right, but they learned absolutely nothing about the underlying structure of the math.

40:16.700 --> 40:18.220
They didn't do the human work.

40:18.420 --> 40:22.020
That is a flawless analogy for geometric alignment loss.

40:22.020 --> 40:31.620
The AI is getting the right answer, but its scratchpad is filled with high vorticity, phase discontinuities, and complete entropy and sensitivity.

40:32.320 --> 40:35.280
It hasn't learned the transformation structure of human meaning.

40:35.800 --> 40:39.140
It has only memorized the coordinate of the destination.

40:39.140 --> 40:49.580
The paper mathematically proves that an AI can have zero endpoint error while simultaneously having massive structural path coherence error.

40:49.580 --> 40:56.440
Man, if that's the case, then our entire metric for testing language models is fundamentally skewed.

40:56.920 --> 41:02.680
We are celebrating the destination, but the AI took a completely alien route to get there.

41:02.680 --> 41:10.360
If an AI doesn't share a biological prior, if it doesn't share those entropy-weighted limitations, those F1 school zones,

41:10.560 --> 41:16.160
then it will never actually think like us, no matter how perfectly it mimics our outputs.

41:16.160 --> 41:21.040
It is basically an alien intelligence wearing a human mask.

41:21.600 --> 41:25.220
As long as it gets the answer right, we just assume it's reasoning like a human.

41:25.660 --> 41:31.980
But the second it encounters a novel high-stakes situation where it has to actively reason through a new problem,

41:32.380 --> 41:37.840
its underlying alien geometry will take over, and we will have absolutely no idea what it's going to do.

41:38.220 --> 41:42.600
Because it doesn't have the CPG tracks guiding it back to safety when it gets confused.

41:42.600 --> 41:46.680
It won't experience a human directional failure.

41:47.180 --> 41:49.380
It will experience an alien failure.

41:49.920 --> 41:54.320
It's a profound critique of current machine learning evaluation metrics.

41:54.920 --> 41:57.640
We are optimizing models for endpoint equivalents,

41:58.320 --> 42:04.600
but Flyxion mathematically demonstrates that true cognitive alignment requires matching the internal constraint functionals.

42:04.600 --> 42:09.200
But wait, if the AI is getting the right answers on the surface,

42:09.560 --> 42:13.080
what does the scratch pad actually look like under a microscope?

42:13.700 --> 42:20.760
Like, what is the literal physical math separating a human thought's propagation from an AI's computation?

42:21.580 --> 42:25.420
This brings us to the deep math of the paper, the appendices,

42:25.780 --> 42:28.240
where Flyxion really looks under the hood.

